
# Abstract

The Arduino ECG Heart Rate Monitor is an embedded healthcare project developed to monitor and analyze heart activity using Electrocardiography (ECG) signals. The system employs an ECG sensor module connected to an Arduino microcontroller to capture electrical impulses generated by the heart. These signals are processed and transmitted to a computer for real-time visualization and monitoring.

The primary objective of this project is to provide a low-cost, portable, and user-friendly solution for heart rate monitoring. The ECG sensor acquires cardiac signals through electrodes placed on the body, while the Arduino processes the analog data and sends it through serial communication. The collected data can be displayed using visualization tools such as the Arduino Serial Plotter.

This project demonstrates the integration of biomedical sensors with embedded systems and highlights the practical applications of microcontrollers in healthcare technology. The developed system can be used for educational purposes, research activities, and basic cardiac monitoring. Future improvements may include wireless communication, cloud-based data storage, and mobile application support for remote health monitoring.
